On the whole, this is a bit of an insult. I find it hard to believe that the finance department of SoE will really complete their usual US and a different tax return for each EU country in which they operate <img border=0 src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif" /> unless of course they arrange it so that the revenue is booked in the local country where the subscribers live (and therefore not subject to US tax).  Also, how come all of the EU has to pay the same rate of VAT/TVA as the UK? Sounds more link a price hike with a view to covering some prospective future liabilities (and more) to me. We are now having to pay more to receive upgrades late, patching during peak times and no customer service in normal business hours <img border=0 src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/mad.gif" />. I really think it is a bit much and gives a real competative advantage to EU-based MMORPG operators (such as Eve Online). I would be interested to find out more about this, just as Kollip says for the principle. I have strong suspicions that EQ1 is being managed relative to its position in the famous Boston Consulting Model - Cash Cow. SoE will make all efforts to reduce costs and increase profits of an established product until it becomes a loss-leader for EQ2.<br>
<br>
On the topic of there being no link between paying tax and consumer rights, I seem to remember the slogan of a reasonably notable ex-colony that recently celebrated its independence as being "No taxation without representation". Cruel irony. <img border=0 src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif" />  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/bscarab5467.showUserPublicProfile?gid=onomatopoeia>onomatopoeia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>SCARAB Initiate</span><br>  Posts: 419<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/8/03 15:01)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fscarab5467frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=127.topic&index=9>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.chater.demon.co.uk/boyatbook.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: VAT to be charged on subscriptions in EU</span><hr size=1> I read a fairly comprehensive FAQ on the tax directive and it seems that the non EU businesses can 'choose' a single country in the EU through which to handle this and use their VAT rate, in order to reduce the admin burden on them (and I guess the EU hopes to encourage them to actually make an effort to collect the tax instead of ignoring it).  I'm fairly sure that Sony wouldn't just charge 17.5% extra and bank the money, that said I wonder how hard it would be to get a VAT invoice from them and how I would go about claiming it back should I need to <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
My Ulan Bator example still stands though - what if Company A has no EU interests at all except customers - no subsidiaries under EU jurastiction for action to be taken against.<br>
<br>
I don't see an advantage to EU based MMPORGs as they all have to pay VAT as well.  I'm fairly sure the change was bought about by AOL who evaded VAT for years in the UK by claiming to be a content provider not providing a tangible service rather than an ISP.<br>
<br>
